<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-06-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="568" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d568">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Hunter</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Burlingame</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 143.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-06-06"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 6, 1865.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your despatch of the 7th of March last,
                            No. 100, with its accompanying copies of a correspondence in the case of
                            Mr. Mills, who appears to have rented a house in Tangchan, thereby
                            exceeding the privileges accorded to foreigners by the treaty, has been
                            received, and your proceedings in the matter are approved.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. HUNTER, <hi rend="italic">Acting
                            Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Anson Burlingame,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,&amp;c.,&amp;c.,</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>